  "binaries": {
    "bin-jc-ginote-0616": {
      "contentType": "text/plain",
      "text": "GI PROGRESS NOTE 6/16/2026\n\n29F with ileocolonic Crohn's disease (dx 2019), s/p laparoscopic ileocecal resection 8/2024 for stricturing disease, on adalimumab 40 mg q2wk + azathioprine 100 mg daily. Colonoscopy 12/2025 showed anastomotic recurrence, Rutgeerts i2b.\n\nINTERVAL HISTORY: Worsening crampy RLQ pain, looser stools (4-5/day, occasional nocturnal), 1.5 kg weight loss since 5/2026. ADHERENCE: Missed 2 adalimumab doses in April-May while traveling for work; restarted on schedule 5/20. Reports frequent ibuprofen use (400-600 mg several times/week) for pain — counseled again to avoid NSAIDs as a flare trigger; suggested acetaminophen.\n\nLABS: CRP 4.2 (5/12) -> 11.8 mg/L today. Fecal calprotectin 620 ug/g (5/12). Hgb 10.8, ferritin 12 — iron deficiency anemia, continue oral iron, consider IV iron if intolerant. WBC 9.4 on azathioprine.\n\nCONTRACEPTION/REPRO: Not on contraception; not currently planning pregnancy. Counseled re: pregnancy planning while on azathioprine and during active disease. Cycles reported as irregular.\n\nASSESSMENT/PLAN:\n1. Crohn's flare with endoscopic postoperative recurrence (i2b) and rising biomarkers — likely partial secondary loss of response vs adherence gap. START prednisone taper: 40 mg x2wk, 20 mg x2wk, 10 mg x2wk. Check adalimumab level + antibodies; discussed escalation to weekly dosing vs switch to ustekinumab/risankizumab pending results.\n2. Strict NSAID avoidance.\n3. Iron deficiency anemia — continue ferrous sulfate every other day.\n4. Return precautions reviewed: fever, worsening focal pain, obstipation, vomiting — present to ED given immunosuppression may mask severity."
    },
    "bin-jc-ednote-1114": {
      "contentType": "text/plain",
      "text": "ED PROVIDER NOTE 11/14/2025 (DISCHARGE)\n\nHPI: 28F with ileocolonic Crohn's s/p ileocecal resection 8/2024, on adalimumab + azathioprine, presenting with 1 day of crampy RLQ pain and nausea. Low-grade temp 37.8 at triage.\n\nED COURSE: Labs notable for mild anemia (Hgb 11.2), WBC 8.9, CRP 22 mg/L. Urine hCG negative. CT abdomen/pelvis with IV contrast: active inflammation of the neo-terminal ileum, wall thickening 8 mm, fat stranding; NO abscess, NO obstruction. Appendix surgically absent. Pain improved with IV fluids and antiemetics. Tolerated PO challenge.\n\nDISPO: Discussed with GI on call — consistent with Crohn's flare/postoperative recurrence. Discharged with GI follow-up within 2 weeks (colonoscopy subsequently scheduled), prednisone NOT started in ED per GI preference. Return precautions: fever, worsening pain, vomiting, obstipation. Counseled that her immunosuppression can mask fever/WBC elevation and to have a low threshold to return."
    },
